and and Wales 2010’ – Table A3.7</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Attached is a table showing the number of offenders remanded in custody and found guilty, by offence, in each year from 2010 to 2013, in England and Wales. This table also shows the average custodial sentence length of those offenders given immediate custody.</p><p> </p><p>On 28th May 2013 committal hearings were abolished nationally as part of wider measures to speed up justice and improve efficiencies in the justice system. Cases are now being sent straight to the Crown Court as soon as it is clear the matter is serious enough rather than having to await a committal hearing. This change in proceedings led to a change in the recording of magistrates’ court remands data. As a result, care should be taken when attempting to identify trends.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara","213353 ; 213354","2014-11-07T14:45:17.1566081Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106360/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106360/answer","213354 - final table.xls","213354 - final table.xls","Offenders remanded in custody","Offenders remanded in custody","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106360/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-11-04","Prisoners on Remand","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many people held on remand in (a) 2010, (b) 2011, (c) 2012 and (d) 2013 were subsequently (i) convicted and (ii) found not guilty.","false","Biography information for Sadiq Khan","Tooting","Sadiq Khan","213356"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106361","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-11-11","<p /> <p>The Government is absolutely clear that abusive and threatening behaviour online is totally unacceptable.</p><p> </p><p>There is a number of offences which may be committed by those abusing others on social media. Internet communication which is grossly offensive or menacing may fall under section 127 of the Communications Act 2003. Sending indecent, grossly offensive or threatening material to another with the purpose of causing distress or anxiety to a person to whom the material is communicated, including by means of the internet, is also an offence under the Malicious Communications Act 1988.</p><p> </p><p>Internet abuse could also amount to an offence under the Protection from Harassment Act 1997 if its distribution is carried out as part of a ‘course of conduct’ which alarms a person or causes distress. Under section 4 of that Act, it is also an offence to pursue a course of conduct that repeatedly puts someone in fear of violence.</p><p> </p><p>Changes to the law being taken forward in the Criminal Justice and Courts Bill will increase the maximum penalty for offences under the Malicious Communications Act 1988 to 2 years imprisonment, and extend the time within which prosecutions under section 127 of the Communications Act 2003 may be brought, to up to three years, as opposed to the current six month limit.</p><p>These steps will help to ensure that people who commit these awful crimes are prosecuted and properly punished.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2014-11-11T17:59:26.6392466Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106361/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106361/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106361/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-11-04","Twitter","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what steps he is taking to discourage aggressive and nasty tweeting.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","213347"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106362","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-11-11","<p>The Sexual Offences (Amendment) Act 1992 prohibits the publication of any information that is likely to lead to a person being identified as the victim of an alleged sexual offence, from the point at which the allegation has been made. But this prohibition does not prevent the complainant’s name from being used in court and therefore would not serve to conceal it from the defendant (if it was not already known to him). In exceptional circumstances a court may make a witness anonymity order under sections 86 to 90 of the Coroners and Justice Act 2009. Such an order prevents the disclosure of the identity of a witness (including the complainant) or any information that might allow the witness to be identified in or in connection with the proceedings except to the judge and jury or magistrates.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2014-11-11T17:39:39.640476Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106362/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106362/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106362/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-11-04","Rape","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what steps his Department has taken to prevent the identity of rape victims becoming known to (a) their alleged assailants and (b) the families of their alleged assailant.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","213350"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106363","Northern Ireland Office","false","2014-11-07","<p>I propose to provide my Rt hon Friend the Prime Minister with a report on the current talks by 28 November. I hope to be able to report positive progress.</p><p> </p>","Chipping Barnet","Mrs Theresa Villiers",,"2014-11-07T11:26:15.2211292Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106363/answer","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106363/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106363/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2014-11-04","Northern Ireland Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, when she expects the political talks that she is chairing in Northern Ireland to conclude; and if she will make it her policy to place a paper on the conclusions of those talks in the Library.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","213427"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106364","Scotland Office","false","2014-11-11","<p>Estimates of the number and proportion of children in relative low income are published in the National Statistics Households Below Average Income (HBAI) series. This information is captured using the Family Resources Survey (FRS) and has been reported since 1998/99. These estimates are available for each financial year up to 2012/13, the latest period for which estimates are available.</p><p>Average figures for three survey years have been combined for region and individual countries; this is because single year estimates are not considered to be sufficiently reliable for geographies at a lower level than the UK. The estimates for Scotland can be found below:</p><p><strong>Estimated number (millions) and proportion of children in relative low income by country and region (Before Housing Costs)</strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p><strong>Number (and percentage) of children in relative low income</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2007/08 – 2009/10</strong></p></td><td><p>0.2 million (20%)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2008/09 – 2010/11</strong></p></td><td><p>0.2 million (19%)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2009/10 – 2011/12</strong></p></td><td><p>0.2 million (17%)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2010/11 – 2012/13</strong></p></td><td><p>0.2 million (17%)</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>(Source: HBAI 2012/13</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Orkney and Shetland","Mr Alistair Carmichael",,"2014-11-11T12:56:36.6481036Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106364/answer","Biography information for Mr Alistair Carmichael","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106364/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106364/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2014-11-04","Children: Poverty","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, what estimate he has made of the number of children in Scotland living in poverty in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Margaret Curran","Glasgow East","Margaret Curran","213245"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106365","Scotland Office","false","2014-11-11","<p>Implementation of the Scottish rate of income tax is being led by an HMRC project with oversight provided by a programme board with representatives from HMRC, HM Treasury, the Scotland Office and Scottish Government. The project is progressing a range of issues associated with defining the detail of the implementation and operation of the Scottish rate and the project is on track to make the necessary changes in readiness for April 2016.</p><p>HMRC will have prime responsibility for informing tax payers about these changes and will work with the Scottish Government to ensure that individuals and business have access to the information they will need.</p><p> </p>","Orkney and Shetland","Mr Alistair Carmichael",,"2014-11-11T13:01:03.0945654Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106365/answer","Biography information for Mr Alistair Carmichael","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106365/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106365/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2014-11-04","Income Tax","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, pursuant to the Answer of 15 October 2014, HC Deb, 15 October 2014, column 286, what details regarding the implementation of the Scottish rate of income tax are still under discussion; when he expects those discussions to conclude; and which government department will have responsibility for providing information to income tax payers about changes to the tax system in Scotland.","false","Biography information for Margaret Curran","Glasgow East","Margaret Curran","213288"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106366","Scotland Office","false","2014-11-11","<p>I have received no representations from the Scottish Government regarding the Living Wage.</p><p> </p>","Orkney and Shetland","Mr Alistair Carmichael",,"2014-11-11T13:02:25.1849943Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106366/answer","Biography information for Mr Alistair Carmichael","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106366/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106366/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2014-11-04","Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, what representations he has received from the Scottish Government on the living wage as defined by the Living Wage Foundation; and if he will place in the Library any such representations.","false","Biography information for Margaret Curran","Glasgow East","Margaret Curran","213289"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106367","Department for Transport","false","2014-11-07","<p>The Department remains committed to providing multiple channels for access to its services to ensure they are available to people who remain either unable or unwilling to use digital services. It does so whilst being mindful of reducing the cost to taxpayers by encouraging the take-up of digital services to as wide a group of users as possible. It does this by making them as easy-to-use as possible in conformance with the Government Digital Service’s Digital-by-Default Service Standard published on GOV.UK.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Before going live every Digital by Default Service developed by the Department for Transport is also required to make sure appropriate Assisted Digital (AD) support is in place to extend the reach of digital services.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p />","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2014-11-07T10:23:27.0463459Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106367/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106367/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106367/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2014-11-04","Electronic Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps his Department and agencies are taking to ensure alternative provision for people unable or unwilling to use digital services.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","213231"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106368","Department for Transport","false","2014-11-10","<p>The two levels of catering specified by the Department for Transport were those chosen by the train operators who are closest to their customers requirements. The train operators continue to be fully engaged in the design of the train.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2014-11-10T11:21:49.8822623Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106368/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106368/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106368/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2014-11-04","Rolling Stock: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what reasons his Department specified only two of the four available levels of catering provision for the mock-ups of Intercity Express Programme train sets inspected by bidders and others stakeholders.","false","Biography information for Mrs Linda Riordan","Halifax","Mrs Linda Riordan","213241"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106369","Department for Transport","false","2014-11-10","<p>The train operators have been fully engaged in the design of the Intercity Express Programme trains and will chose the catering solutions that they feel best suits their customer needs.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2014-11-10T11:17:25.0706477Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106369/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106369/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106369/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2014-11-04","Rolling Stock: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will take steps to ensure that the fleet of trains his Department has procured through the Intercity Express Programme for service on the (a) Great Western and (b) East Coast Main Lines are fitted with the full catering provision of galley kitchen, restaurant service, at-seat first class service with meals cooked on board, re-generated meals served at-seat, buffet and trolley service.","false","Biography information for Mrs Linda Riordan","Halifax","Mrs Linda Riordan","213212"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106370","Department for Transport","false","2014-11-10","<p>Decisions on staffing arrangements on the Great Western and East Coast Main Lines are a matter for the Train Operating Company (TOC) and Hitachi.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2014-11-10T11:19:30.4886631Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106370/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106370/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106370/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2014-11-04","Rolling Stock: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment has been made of the likely effect on rail (a) guards, (b) maintenance and (c) catering jobs from the introduction of the Intercity Express Programme fleet on the (i) Great Western and (ii) East Coast Main Lines.","false","Biography information for Mrs Linda Riordan","Halifax","Mrs Linda Riordan","213213"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106371","Department for Transport","false","2014-11-10","<p>This will be a matter for the train operators on the Great Western and East Coast Main Lines.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2014-11-10T11:20:37.5520244Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106371/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106371/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106371/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2014-11-04","Rolling Stock: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many rail (a) guards, (b) maintenance and (c) catering jobs will be created on the (i) Great Western and (ii) East Coast Main Lines as a result of the procurement of new rolling stock through the Intercity Express Programme.","false","Biography information for Mrs Linda Riordan","Halifax","Mrs Linda Riordan","213214"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106372","Department for Transport","false","2014-11-11","<p>A total of 716.4 additional lane miles are planned over the next five years. This consists of schemes both currently under construction and those planned to start construction within the next five years.</p><p> </p><p>There are currently fourteen schemes in construction that will deliver 239.9 additional lane miles.</p><p> </p><p>A further twenty two schemes are currently scheduled to start construction within the next five years and they will add an additional 476.5 lane miles.</p><p> </p><p>By way of context, five schemes have been started and already completed under the current Administration, adding 64.4 additional lane miles.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2014-11-11T13:55:55.9657807Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106372/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106372/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106372/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2014-11-04","Roads: Construction","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many new miles of motorway and trunk road are planned for the next five years.","false","Biography information for John Redwood","Wokingham","Mr John Redwood","213197"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106373","Department for Transport","false","2014-11-11","<p>The Mayor of London is responsible for this matter. I understand from Transport for London that the reduction in the speed limit to 30 mph was a permanent measure, and that there are no plans to revert back to the 40 mph speed limit on the Hammersmith Flyover. This is because during the strengthening work prior to the Olympic Games in 2012, the speed limit on the carriageway was permanently reduced from 40 mph to 30 mph to maintain road safety. This was due to the reduction in road width required to enable the installation of the post-tensioning system in the central reserve. There are still some strengthening and bridge bearing replacement works to be carried out and these are currently being delivered.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2014-11-11T12:35:05.5206363Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106373/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106373/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106373/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2014-11-04","A4: Hammersmith and Fulham","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, when the temporary lower speed limit on the A4 Hammersmith flyover will be lifted.","false","Biography information for John Redwood","Wokingham","Mr John Redwood","213198"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106374","Department for Transport","false","2014-11-10","<p>The budget for new camera installations on the strategic road network to the end of this financial year (2014-15) is £900k.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2014-11-10T16:21:25.3697396Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106374/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106374/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106374/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2014-11-04","Roads: Cameras","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the budget is for new camera installations on national motorways and trunk roads this year.","false","Biography information for John Redwood","Wokingham","Mr John Redwood","213199"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106375","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-11-11","<p /> <p>This Government takes recovery and enforcement of financial impositions very seriously and remains committed to finding new ways to ensure impositions are paid and to trace those who do not pay. This is why there has been a year on year increase in the amount of financial penalties collected over the last three years.</p><p> </p><p>It is not possible to state how much was collected for specific offences without incurring disproportionate costs as this answer could only be provided by a manual search of all live and closed fine accounts.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2014-11-11T17:05:45.0499775Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106375/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106375/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106375/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-11-04","Road Traffic Offences: Fines","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how much was raised in fines for road traffic offences in (a) 2009-10 and (b) 2013-14.","false","Biography information for John Redwood","Wokingham","Mr John Redwood","213200"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106376","Department for Transport","false","2014-11-10","<p>The speed limit of 50 mph was set in 2009 to allow safe merging of vehicles, especially HGVs, which need to move from lane 3 into lane 1 at the end of the M25/M3 merge.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2014-11-10T16:22:35.729343Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106376/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106376/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106376/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2014-11-04","M3: Surrey","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, for what reason the speed limit west on the M3 beyond the M25 junction has been set at 50 mph.","false","Biography information for John Redwood","Wokingham","Mr John Redwood","213201"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106377","Department for Transport","false","2014-11-10","<p>The Highways Agency is responsible for operating, maintaining and improving England’s strategic road network which comprises approximately 4,300 miles of motorways and all-purpose trunk roads.</p><p> </p><p>Approximately 398 miles of motorway (excluding slip roads) are subject to speed restrictions of under 70 mph. 33 miles are permanent speed restrictions and 365 miles are temporary speed restrictions (as of 05 November 2014).</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2014-11-10T16:23:30.5546643Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106377/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106377/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106377/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2014-11-04","Motorways: Speed Limits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many miles of national motorway are subject to speed restrictions of under 70 mph.","false","Biography information for John Redwood","Wokingham","Mr John Redwood","213202"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106378","Department for Transport","false","2014-11-10","<p>These are temporary speed enforcement cameras, which will be in place as part of the traffic management during several M4 maintenance and improvement schemes.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2014-11-10T16:25:02.2409557Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106378/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106378/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106378/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2014-11-04","M4: Cameras","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the purpose is of the new cameras being installed on the M4.","false","Biography information for John Redwood","Wokingham","Mr John Redwood","213203"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106379","Wales Office","false","2014-11-11","<p>Following the outcome of the judicial review in March, NS&amp;I has reinstated Welsh language services provided under its Welsh language scheme. NS&amp;I’s reinstated Welsh language pages can be accessed online via: <a title="http://www.nsandi.com/cymraeg" href="http://www.nsandi.com/cymraeg" target="_blank">http://www.nsandi.com/cymraeg</a>.</p><p> </p>","Vale of Glamorgan","Alun Cairns",,"2014-11-11T11:45:11.0364916Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106379/answer","Biography information for Alun Cairns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106379/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106379/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2014-11-04","Welsh Language","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, what changes there have been in Welsh language provision at Departments providing services to residents of Wales since the judicial review of the National Savings Scheme.","false","Biography information for Mr Mark Williams","Ceredigion","Mr Mark Williams","213221"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106380","Wales Office","false","2014-11-11","<p>The Government is fully committed to the Welsh language and fully committed to providing Government services in the Welsh language where there is demand. The Wales Office is currently undertaking a review of Government services provided in Welsh to determine how they can better meet the needs of Welsh speakers in a reasonable, proportionate and cost-effective way. An official has been seconded from the Welsh Language Commissioner’s office to lead this review.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Vale of Glamorgan","Alun Cairns",,"2014-11-11T11:47:28.3274225Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106380/answer","Biography information for Alun Cairns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106380/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106380/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2014-11-04","Welsh Language","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, what recent assessment he has made for the need for further provision for access to government services in Welsh.","false","Biography information for Mr Mark Williams","Ceredigion","Mr Mark Williams","213222"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106381","Wales Office","false","2014-11-11","<p>The Government is fully committed to the Welsh language, and to providing Government services in Welsh where there is demand. Ten Government Departments have Welsh language schemes, approved in accordance with the Welsh Language Act 1993. These include Departments delivering key public services in Wales, such as the Ministry of Justice and the Department for Work and Pensions.</p><p> </p>","Vale of Glamorgan","Alun Cairns",,"2014-11-11T11:49:00.3169644Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106381/answer","Biography information for Alun Cairns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106381/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106381/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2014-11-04","Welsh Language","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, how many Government departments have a Welsh language service.","false","Biography information for Mr Mark Williams","Ceredigion","Mr Mark Williams","213223"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106382","Wales Office","false","2014-11-10","<p>The Wales Office is reviewing its electronic records which were closed in 2008 with a view to releasing to the National Archives. The Department currently has 6 members of staff undertaking the review of records in conjunction with their other duties.</p><p> </p>","Vale of Glamorgan","Alun Cairns",,"2014-11-10T11:26:11.6001707Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106382/answer","Biography information for Alun Cairns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106382/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106382/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2014-11-04","Public Records","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, what targets have been set for the release of his Department's records to the National Archives; what progress has been made in meeting those targets; and how many staff in his Department are engaged in reviewing records for this purpose.","false","Biography information for Lord Beith","Berwick-upon-Tweed","Sir Alan Beith","213244"
